# Understanding The Relays

## Bosch Relay Pinout

### Pin 85
Relay coil negative

### Pin 86
Relay coil positive

### Pin 30
Common contact

### Pin 87
Normally Open (NO)

### Pin 87a
Normally Closed (NC)

---

# Relay A — Starter Cut-Off Relay (SR)

## Purpose

Stops the starter motor working once the engine starts.

---

# Relay A Wiring

| Pin | Connect To |
|----|-------------|
| 85 | Ground |
| 86 | Yellow alternator trigger |
| 30 | Red/White from starter button |
| 87a | Red/White to starter solenoid |
| 87 | Not used |

---

# Relay A Operation

## Engine OFF

Relay is relaxed.

30 connects to 87a.

Starter button works normally.

---

## Engine RUNNING

Yellow wire energises relay.

30 disconnects from 87a.

Starter motor disabled.

---

# Relay B — Headlight Relay (LR)

## Purpose

Turns headlight on after engine starts.

Keeps headlight on until ignition switched off.

---

# Relay B Wiring

| Pin | Connect To |
|----|-------------|
| 85 | Ground |
| 86 | Trigger/latch junction node |
| 30 | Switched +12V from lighting fuse |
| 87 | Headlight output |
| 87a | Not used |

---

# THE MOST IMPORTANT PART — PIN 86 NODE

This is the most critical connection in the entire project.

At Relay B Pin 86 you MUST join:

1. Wire from diode
2. Wire from resistor
3. Wire into relay pin 86

All three MUST connect together.

If this node is wrong:
- the relay will not latch
- the headlight will switch off
- the system will not behave correctly

---

# Diode Wiring

## Purpose

Allows startup trigger voltage to reach Relay B.

Prevents 12V from feeding back into the alternator.

---

# Correct Diode Orientation

IMPORTANT:

The stripe on the diode MUST face Relay B.

Correct:

Yellow trigger → diode → Relay B pin 86 node

Wrong:

Relay B → diode → Yellow trigger

If installed backwards:
- headlight relay will not work correctly
- fuse blowing may occur
- alternator feedback problems may occur

---

# Resistor Wiring

## Purpose

Keeps Relay B energised after startup.

This is called a latch circuit.

---

# Correct Resistor Wiring

One side:
- Relay B pin 87

Other side:
- Relay B pin 86 node

The resistor is NOT connected inline with the diode.

The resistor is a separate return path.

---

# Optional Flyback Diode

Highly recommended for electronic ignition systems.

## Purpose

Protects electronics from relay coil voltage spikes.

---

# Flyback Diode Wiring

Across Relay B coil:

| Connection | Location |
|-----------|----------|
| Stripe side | Pin 86 |
| Non-stripe side | Pin 85 |

---

# System Operation

## Key ON — Engine NOT Running

- Starter works
- Headlight OFF

---

## Engine Starts

- Yellow trigger energises relays
- Starter disabled
- Headlight turns ON

---

## Engine Stops (Key Still ON)

- Headlight stays ON
- Starter re-enabled once relay relaxes

---

# Common Mistakes

## Diode Installed Backwards

Symptoms:
- headlight problems
- relay problems
- feedback issues

Fix:
- reverse diode orientation

---

## Resistor Connected Wrong

Symptoms:
- headlight switches OFF when engine stops
- relay chatter
- unstable operation

Fix:
- ensure resistor connects from pin 87 back to pin 86 node

---

## Bad Ground

Symptoms:
- relays clicking weakly
- intermittent behaviour

Fix:
- clean chassis ground
- ensure good continuity

---

# Testing Procedure

## Step 1
Turn ignition ON.

Expected:
- starter works
- headlight OFF

---

## Step 2
Start engine.

Expected:
- headlight ON
- starter disabled

---

## Step 3
Stop engine with ignition still ON.

Expected:
- headlight stays ON

